# PRIVATE - personal cheat sheet (do not show on camera)

Active demo folder for <MODEL_SPOKEN>.

## What is set up

- A single general-purpose vLLM container `<CONTAINER>` runs as standing
  infrastructure on the server. It is idle (sleep entrypoint, `--init`) and stays up.
- Serving a model = launching `vllm serve` inside that container via `docker exec`.
- The vLLM compile cache lives on the host disk at `<VLLM_CACHE>` and is mounted in,
  so graphs survive process kills and container recreation.
- Between takes we just kill the `vllm serve` process; the container stays up. The
  next run relaunches the model from warm cache and shows the engine warmup.

## The prompt to say on camera

> run <MODEL_SPOKEN> on my Instinct server at <SERVER_IP> with vLLM and give me the endpoint

## Flow (every take)

1. Stage the box from the laptop:

       cd ~/<DEMO_FOLDER> && ./stage.sh

2. (optional) live server view in a second terminal:

       ./watch.sh        # or: ssh <SSH_USER>@<SERVER_IP> then ./check_docker_log.sh

3. Open Claude in this folder:

       claude --dangerously-skip-permissions

4. Say the prompt. Endpoint + table in roughly two minutes.

5. Point the client at it:

       ssh <SSH_USER>@<SERVER_IP>
       ./set_hermes_custom_model.sh
       hermes chat

## Reset between takes

Run `./stage.sh` again before the next take.

## Timing

- First-ever launch after the cache mount changed: ~240s (one-time, cache populate).
- Warm relaunch after a process kill: ~90s + Claude orchestration. This is the demo path.

## What is honest to say if asked

- The weights are cached on the box (no download).
- We keep a general-purpose vLLM serving container running; serving a model starts it
  inside that container. The ~2 min is the engine warming up (weights into HBM,
  replaying compiled graphs, allocating the KV cache).
- A brand-new model from a cold box takes longer; we pre-stage to stay in budget.
